	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />What whould be the difference between using CHR-ROM and CHR-RAM?
<br />
<br />Do they both hold graphical data?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Tue Apr 11, 2006 1:00 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yeah, they both hold graphics.  With CHR-ROM the graphics are all pre-defined, with CHR-RAM you'd make some code for the CPU to write the graphics to RAM and update as needed (instead of switching CHR-ROM banks).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Tue Apr 11, 2006 5:01 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Advantages of CHR ROM are that switching is faster and that it works with more special-purpose mappers. Advantages of CHR RAM are that switching can be done in smaller units and that data can be compressed.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

